</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Males of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haplodrassus</taxonomicName>
species by the peculiar thin embolus with an inner spur-like process, and also the peculiar shape of the RTA, which is not indented and has a claw-like tip (Figs 32-34).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Well described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 37" title="Spiders of the genera Drassodes and Haplodrassus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) from Israel." volume="50" year="2004">Levy (2004)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Figures 32-34. Males of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
from Azerbaijan: 32 bulbus, apical view 33 RTA, retrolateral view 34 palp, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Spain, Corsica, Italy (mainland and Sicily), Turkey, Israel and Azerbaijan (
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 37" title="Spiders of the genera Drassodes and Haplodrassus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) from Israel." volume="50" year="2004">Levy 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Platnick 2012</bibRefCitation>
; present data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
is a new species record for the fauna of Azerbaijan, Caucasus and the former Soviet Union. Azerbaijan is the easternmost point of the known distribution range.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
